<p>Solar production in South Carolina follows predictable seasonal patterns, with peak generation occurring from April through September when cooling demands are highest. Summer months typically see 15-20% higher production compared to winter months, creating natural alignment between energy generation and consumption patterns. The state experiences minimal snow coverage that could impair panel performance, and hurricane season impacts are generally limited to brief periods of reduced generation. Modern solar panels are designed to withstand wind speeds up to 140 mph, making them suitable for South Carolina's occasional severe weather events.</p>

<p>Geographic variations across the state show Charleston and the Lowcountry region receiving the highest solar irradiance levels, followed closely by the Columbia metropolitan area and Greenville-Spartanburg region in the Upstate. Even areas with slightly lower solar resource still provide excellent economics for solar installations due to the state's incentive structure and electricity rates. Roof orientation and tilt become critical factors for maximizing production, with south-facing roofs at 30-35¬∞ tilt providing optimal performance, though southwest and southeast orientations can achieve 85-90% of optimal production.</p>

