<h2>HVAC Systems in South Carolina</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>South Carolina's humid subtropical climate creates unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state experiences hot, humid summers with average temperatures ranging from 80-90¬∞F and relative humidity often exceeding 70%, creating substantial cooling loads from May through September. Winter temperatures are generally mild, with averages between 45-65¬∞F, meaning heating demands are moderate compared to northern climates. This climate pattern makes heat pump systems particularly attractive, as they can provide efficient cooling in summer and adequate heating during the mild winter months.</p>

<p>Humidity control becomes a critical factor in South Carolina HVAC design, as high moisture levels can create comfort issues and indoor air quality concerns even when temperatures are controlled. Modern HVAC systems must balance temperature control with dehumidification, often requiring variable-speed equipment and properly sized systems to achieve optimal performance. Oversized systems can lead to short cycling and inadequate humidity removal, while undersized systems may struggle during peak summer conditions. The coastal regions face additional challenges with salt air corrosion, requiring specialized equipment coatings and more frequent maintenance schedules.</p>

<p>Energy consumption patterns in South Carolina show pronounced seasonal variations, with summer cooling representing 40-50% of annual electricity usage for typical homes. Peak demand periods align with afternoon and early evening hours when outside temperatures and solar heat gain are highest. This creates excellent synergy opportunities with solar panel systems, as peak solar production often coincides with peak cooling demands. The relatively mild winter heating requirements mean that efficient heat pump systems can maintain comfortable temperatures while consuming minimal electricity compared to electric resistance heating.</p>

